# Observability Rules

## Structured Logging

- Use `structlog` (or an equivalent structured logging library) throughout the backend — never use `print()` for observability purposes.
- Every log entry must include at minimum: `timestamp`, `level`, `module`, `message`.
- Log output must be machine-parseable (JSON format in production, human-readable in development).
- Do not construct log strings via f-string concatenation — pass structured key-value pairs to the logger.

## Pipeline Stage Logs

Every log entry emitted at a pipeline stage boundary must include:

- `run_id` — UUID of the current pipeline run
- `stage_name` — name of the pipeline stage (e.g., `fetch_signals`, `normalize`, `rank`)
- `record_count` — number of records processed in this stage
- `error_count` — number of records that failed processing
- `duration_ms` — wall-clock time for the stage in milliseconds

Log at `INFO` level on success, `WARNING` if error_count > 0, `ERROR` if the stage aborted.

## Job Logs

Every Celery job or scheduled task must log on start and completion with:

- `job_name` — task name as registered with Celery
- `run_id` — pipeline run identifier
- `started_at` — ISO 8601 datetime
- `ended_at` — ISO 8601 datetime
- `status` — `success`, `failed`, or `partial`
- `error_summary` — brief description of failures if `status != success`

## Exception Logs

When catching and logging exceptions, always include:

- Exception type (class name)
- Exception message
- Full stack trace (use `exc_info=True` or structlog's exception handling)
- Context dict with relevant identifiers (e.g., `topic_id`, `run_id`, `source_name`)

Do not swallow exceptions silently — either re-raise or log with full context and mark the record as failed.

## Health and Readiness Endpoints

### GET /health

- Returns HTTP 200 with `{"status": "ok", "timestamp": "<ISO 8601>"}`.
- Must NOT require database connectivity — this is a pure liveness probe.
- Must respond in under 100ms under all conditions.
- Used by load balancers and container orchestrators.

### GET /ready

- Returns HTTP 200 only when the service is ready to handle requests.
- Must verify and report on:
  - Database connectivity (can execute a trivial query)
  - Redis connectivity (can ping)
  - Last pipeline run summary (timestamp, status, record counts)
  - Any critical configuration errors detected at startup
- Returns HTTP 503 if any critical dependency is unavailable.
- Response body must include per-dependency status, not just a top-level boolean.

## Pipeline Status Endpoint

- `GET /v1/pipeline/status` must return a list of recent pipeline runs.
- Each run entry must include: `run_id`, `started_at`, `ended_at`, `status`, per-stage summaries (stage name, record count, error count, duration).
- This endpoint is the primary operator visibility surface for pipeline health — keep it accurate and up to date.

## MVP Scope Constraint

- Do not implement full OpenTelemetry instrumentation (traces, metrics exporters) in the MVP.
- Design log and context structures so that OTel can be added later without restructuring log calls (use bound loggers with context vars that map cleanly to OTel span attributes).
- No Prometheus metrics endpoint required in MVP — but do not make it structurally impossible to add one.

## Performance Discipline

- Do not emit per-record log entries inside processing loops — log summaries at stage boundaries.
- If you need per-record debug output, gate it behind a `DEBUG` level check or a feature flag.
- Expensive serialization (e.g., formatting large dicts) must not happen unless the log level is active.

## Startup Logs

At application startup, the following must be logged at `INFO` level and confirmed:

- Settings loaded (log config source, not secrets)
- Database connection established
- Redis connection established
- All routers registered (list of route prefixes)
- Any critical warnings (e.g., missing optional config, degraded mode)

Startup must fail fast with a clear `ERROR` log if a required dependency is unreachable.
